## 4. Pre-classified intentional controls (scanners WILL flag these)

<!-- guidance: Some deliberate security controls trip scanners by design.
Pre-classifying them turns the scan's noise into ready dossier entries before
the scan even runs. Each MUST still be a real control in the code (cite it) —
this section is not a place to pre-excuse genuine findings. Candidates a DAST
commonly flags as "issues" that are actually controls: a method-not-allowed
response on a path that intentionally serves no stream; an
anti-enumeration endpoint that returns a uniform 200 regardless of input;
lockout enforced out-of-band (cache/store) and thus invisible to a black-box
scan; rate-limit 429s mid-scan; an endpoint that returns a bare status with no
body on bad input (anti-forgery); an anonymous-by-spec registration endpoint
(bounded by rate limit + downstream gates); missing-header reports on routes
where the header IS set by middleware (verify case-by-case). Use a full §3
block per entry, OR the compact table below when the control is simple and the
code citation is unambiguous. Anything the scan reports that is NOT here is a
candidate REAL finding → triage in §5, do not blanket-dismiss. -->

| Finding ID | What the scanner reports | Disposition | Why it is intentional | Evidence (file) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| {{FINDING_ID}} | {{SCANNER_REPORT}} | {{FP_OR_EXPECTED}} | {{WHY_INTENTIONAL}} | {{CODE_CITATION}} |

**Genuine findings are NOT pre-classified.** Anything the scan reports that is
not in the table above is a candidate real finding → triage it in §5 (fix or
justify). Treat as serious regardless of the scanner's severity label: any
reflected/stored XSS, any auth bypass (a protected call succeeding without a
valid credential), any cross-tenant data in a response, any secret in a
response/header/error body, any transport downgrade.

